messages.content: You are tasked with creating a structured output from the provided user message.

I found three distinct endpoints exposed by the invoices router (the router is mounted at the "/invoices" prefix in index.js). Below I list each full HTTP request path (params in curly braces) and whether each HTTP method is accepted according to the code (no assumptions about Express implicit behavior are made).

Endpoint 1
- Full path: /invoices/count
- allMethods: false
- HEAD: false
- POST: false
- OPTIONS: false
- TRACE: false
- GET: true
- PUT: false
- DELETE: false
- PATCH: false

Endpoint 2
- Full path: /invoices/{id}
- allMethods: false
- HEAD: false
- POST: false
- OPTIONS: false
- TRACE: false
- GET: true
- PUT: false
- DELETE: true
- PATCH: true

Endpoint 3
- Full path: /invoices
- allMethods: false
- HEAD: false
- POST: true
- OPTIONS: false
- TRACE: false
- GET: true
- PUT: false
- DELETE: false
- PATCH: false

Explanation / mapping
- index.js mounts the invoices router with: app.use('/invoices', invoiceRoutes). That prefix is therefore prepended to every route defined in routes/invoices.js.
- routes/invoices.js defines:
  - router.get('/count', getTotalCount) → full path /invoices/count, accepts GET only.
  - router.get('/:id', getInvoice) → full path /invoices/{id}, accepts GET.
  - router.get('/', getInvoicesByUser) → full path /invoices, accepts GET.
  - router.post('/', createInvoice) → full path /invoices, accepts POST.
  - router.patch('/:id', updateInvoice) → full path /invoices/{id}, accepts PATCH.
  - router.delete('/:id', deleteInvoice) → full path /invoices/{id}, accepts DELETE.
- There are no router.all, router.options, router.head, router.trace, or router.put handlers in the provided code, so those methods are marked false. (Per your instruction I did not assume implicit Express behavior such as automatic HEAD handling for GET routes.)
